WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.440 --> 00:00:04.390
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: Good afternoon, everyone, and
welcome to the Friday App Review.

00:00:04.390 --> 00:00:05.390
My name is Reto Meier.

00:00:05.390 --> 00:00:06.490
I'm joined by Fred Chung.

00:00:06.490 --> 00:00:07.490
&gt;&gt;Fred Chung: Good afternoon.

00:00:07.490 --> 00:00:09.500
&gt;&gt;Meier: We're going to take a look at some
apps today.

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:14.719
We asked you guys for some suggestions for
recipe apps, and you did not give us any.

00:00:14.719 --> 00:00:17.860
Which means one of two things: either you
guys don't like recipe apps, or there aren't

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:18.860
any recipe apps.

00:00:18.860 --> 00:00:20.280
&gt;&gt;Chung: There was such an overwhelming crowd.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:21.470
&gt;&gt;Meier: Yes.

00:00:21.470 --> 00:00:25.290
[laughs] You just couldn't pick from amongst
the very many good ones.

00:00:25.290 --> 00:00:26.370
&gt;&gt;Chung: There are just too many.

00:00:26.370 --> 00:00:27.370
&gt;&gt;Meier: Apparently so.

00:00:27.370 --> 00:00:30.920
So what we're going to do this week instead
is have a look at some of our favorites.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:32.589
Fred's got a couple of food related apps.

00:00:32.589 --> 00:00:34.879
Which ones are you going to take a look at
today?

00:00:34.879 --> 00:00:35.879
&gt;&gt;Chung: Yeah.

00:00:35.879 --> 00:00:38.379
We're going to have a look at My Food and
BigOven.

00:00:38.379 --> 00:00:39.379
&gt;&gt;Meier: Excellent.

00:00:39.379 --> 00:00:44.910
The reason I was asking you guys for recipe
apps was because I didn't know of any goods

00:00:44.910 --> 00:00:45.910
ones.

00:00:45.910 --> 00:00:49.140
So rather than spend time looking at apps
I've never looked at before, I'm going to

00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:52.620
take a look at some of my favorite apps, in
terms of apps that I use a lot of.

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:56.469
And that's Series Guide, IMDb, and, if we
get time, I'm going to take a look at TripIt

00:00:56.469 --> 00:00:57.469
as well.

00:00:57.469 --> 00:01:01.710
Now, before we get started, I just want to
clarify a little bit about what we're trying

00:01:01.710 --> 00:01:03.850
to achieve here at the Friday App Review.

00:01:03.850 --> 00:01:09.250
Unlike a lot of the review shows that you
may have seen, we're not really focused on

00:01:09.250 --> 00:01:12.890
giving a fair and balanced evaluation of what
are some great apps that we think you guys

00:01:12.890 --> 00:01:14.400
should be installing.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:16.710
We're part of a developer relations team here
at Android.

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:20.410
Our focus is really on trying to help developers
build better apps.

00:01:20.410 --> 00:01:24.790
So to do that, whenever we look at these apps,
we're really trying to dissect them, take

00:01:24.790 --> 00:01:28.140
them apart, see what they're doing right,
see what they're doing wrong, and really try

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:33.000
and create a learning experience so that other
app developers can learn from the mistakes

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.780
and successes of these other apps.

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:39.820
Really, the app review doesn't make a lot
of sense as a title, so we're actually going

00:01:39.820 --> 00:01:43.480
to change the name of our show live on air.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:47.540
So from this point on, we're going to become
the Friday App Clinic.

00:01:47.540 --> 00:01:53.270
Now, in order to maintain that new branding,
I have some props.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:55.910
I'm going to just get off camera and get my
props.

00:01:55.910 --> 00:01:57.230
[shuffling noises]

00:01:57.230 --> 00:02:01.850
&gt;&gt;Chung: Reto's going to come back soon.

00:02:01.850 --> 00:02:02.850
[laughs]

00:02:02.850 --> 00:02:03.870
&gt;&gt;Meier: [laughs] Don't panic.

00:02:03.870 --> 00:02:09.280
[more shuffling] And Daniel, if our producer
off camera can also switch our title, so that

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:10.280
we can become the Friday App Clinic, that
would be fantastic.

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:14.780
&gt;&gt;Chung: We have double to size of our production
team.

00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:16.170
&gt;&gt;Meier: [laughs] That's right.

00:02:16.170 --> 00:02:17.560
Twice as many producers.

00:02:17.560 --> 00:02:22.050
&gt;&gt;Off-camera engineer: Oh, did you remember
to tell your off-camera engineer to include

00:02:22.050 --> 00:02:26.230
your new title in his title set?

00:02:26.230 --> 00:02:27.830
&gt;&gt;Meier: Yes.

00:02:27.830 --> 00:02:30.230
[laughs] One moment.

00:02:30.230 --> 00:02:35.180
That's all right, we have all the time in
the world.

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:36.180
I have my--

00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:37.180
&gt;&gt;Off-camera engineer: You have an hour.

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:38.180
&gt;&gt;Meier: I have an hour.

00:02:38.180 --> 00:02:39.180
&gt;&gt;Off-camera engineer: Actually, more like
45 minutes.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:40.180
&gt;&gt;Chung: We have 45 minutes.

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:41.180
That's close to an hour.

00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:42.180
&gt;&gt;Meier: 45 minutes?!

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:43.180
Oh, then we should get this shit sorted out.

00:02:43.180 --> 00:02:44.180
All right.

00:02:44.180 --> 00:02:46.070
We have our doctor Droids.

00:02:46.070 --> 00:02:48.640
I have my lab coat.

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:50.460
&gt;&gt;Chung: You have a lab coat.

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:51.460
Where's mine?

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:52.460
&gt;&gt;Meier: You have to bring your own coat.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:53.460
&gt;&gt;Chung: I have to order it.

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:54.460
&gt;&gt;Meier: Yeah.

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:55.460
I mean, come on, man!

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:56.800
&gt;&gt;Chung: That's what that box was for.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:02:57.800
&gt;&gt;Meier: Absolutely.

00:02:57.800 --> 00:02:59.680
You need to order your own equipment.

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:01.480
&gt;&gt;Chung: Just pretend this is a white--

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:03.310
&gt;&gt;Meier: This is a white coat.

00:03:03.310 --> 00:03:04.310
Absolutely.

00:03:04.310 --> 00:03:05.310
&gt;&gt;Chung: Can you color correct it?

00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:06.310
&gt;&gt;Meier: Color correct it.

00:03:06.310 --> 00:03:07.360
Yeah, you should have worn at least a green
shirt, so we can make due.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:08.360
&gt;&gt;Chung: Next time, maybe.

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:09.360
&gt;&gt;Meier: That's right.

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:10.360
That's right.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:11.940
I snuck this up on Fred here, as well.

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:13.180
This is his first clinic too.

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:16.310
So I can be the official clinician.

00:03:16.310 --> 00:03:20.020
[laughs] And Fred can continue to be a reviewer.

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:21.020
So let's get started.

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:22.140
Let's have a look at one of your apps.

00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:23.240
Let's start with--.

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:24.590
Where would you like to start?

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:25.590
&gt;&gt;Chung: Yeah.

00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:28.930
I'm excited to stick to something that is
related to recipes.

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:35.160
Both of these apps, as I mentioned earlier,
my Food and BigOven-- if we could switch to

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:37.090
the tablet, please.

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:42.819
Both of these apps try to tackle the problem
where you're trying to figure out what's for

00:03:42.819 --> 00:03:43.819
dinner.

00:03:43.819 --> 00:03:49.069
Then you have to figure out what kind of dishes
you would like to get.

00:03:49.069 --> 00:03:55.270
After the preparation stage, you can translate
the types of ingredients into some sort of

00:03:55.270 --> 00:03:56.270
shopping list.

00:03:56.270 --> 00:03:59.680
These two apps try to solve this problem.

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:02.250
They try to do it a little bit differently.

00:04:02.250 --> 00:04:06.170
Why don't we have a look at my Food?

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:10.190
As soon as this app is launched, it's pretty
self-explanatory.

00:04:10.190 --> 00:04:18.580
It's got three high level menu items that
you can pick from: shopping list, recipes,

00:04:18.580 --> 00:04:19.790
and meal planner.

00:04:19.790 --> 00:04:26.160
All of these, very prominently displayed,
which is nice, which makes it very easy for

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:27.160
users to comprehend.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:35.630
You would go into recipe first, but before
diving into the content of recipe, I like

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:40.910
to highlight that when I tap on any of these
targets, there's no touch feedback.

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:44.780
I would, like what we've been asking developers
to do.

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:51.580
When you come up with graphics icons, be sure
to have different, have them represented in

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:56.430
different states to represent the natural
state, focus state, and pressed state.

00:04:56.430 --> 00:04:58.940
&gt;&gt;Meier: That's really important, particularly
for accessibility.

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:02.970
If you want blind users to be able to use
your app, or even just people who are using

00:05:02.970 --> 00:05:08.490
accessibility type features to make it more
easy, then having those touch target selectors

00:05:08.490 --> 00:05:10.200
is really important.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:14.870
&gt;&gt;Chung: Before going to any of these, let's
have a quick look at the menu.

00:05:14.870 --> 00:05:20.310
There's help, settings, the items that, the
usual suspects, basically, things that you

00:05:20.310 --> 00:05:22.900
would expect to see under the overflow menu.

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:23.900
&gt;&gt;Meier: Absolutely.

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:28.570
I want to point out, as well here, that looking
at this main screen here as well, you can

00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:31.730
see that we've actually got an action bar,
which is good.

00:05:31.730 --> 00:05:36.770
But in this case, I think actually it would
make a lot of sense to have an action bar

00:05:36.770 --> 00:05:41.710
which was perhaps translucent, because you've
got this whole screen effect here where it's

00:05:41.710 --> 00:05:45.100
this immersive thing, completely custom controls.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:48.370
The action bar almost looks a little bit plunked
on top.

00:05:48.370 --> 00:05:52.690
Perhaps changing the color of your action
bar to match the background or have a translucent

00:05:52.690 --> 00:05:55.070
action bar would be an interesting design
choice.

00:05:55.070 --> 00:05:57.979
&gt;&gt;Chung: I actually like the suggestion on
translucent.

00:05:57.979 --> 00:06:00.860
Let's have a look at the recipe screens.

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:08.259
As you can see, in this drop down box, there
are different types of occasions like starter,

00:06:08.259 --> 00:06:10.490
sides, dinner, whatever.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:13.680
There are different categories that you can
choose from.

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:16.650
It prepopulates it with a bunch of delicious
dishes.

00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:18.910
&gt;&gt;Meier: [laughs] Absolutely.

00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:23.389
&gt;&gt;Chung: You can swipe food, the selection
of dishes.

00:06:23.389 --> 00:06:26.490
These are the top level recipe items.

00:06:26.490 --> 00:06:35.020
What you can do is look at the various ingredients
and the steps involved in the preparation

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:36.020
of the dish.

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:41.139
What I would suggest is that when you have
a tablet, the most probable use case is someone

00:06:41.139 --> 00:06:43.000
using your app in a kitchen.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.930
I might be sitting three to four feet away
from the tablet.

00:06:47.930 --> 00:06:51.400
The font size as it stands is a little bit
too small.

00:06:51.400 --> 00:06:53.520
&gt;&gt;Meier: Yeah, it is, it's a little small.

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:56.820
&gt;&gt;Chung: I'm having a hard time in reading
the text.

00:06:56.820 --> 00:06:57.820
&gt;&gt;Meier: Exactly.

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:01.400
What you want to really have is so that you
can set up the tablet on your kitchen bench,

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:03.919
probably a little further away from the food--
&gt;&gt;Chung: Definitely.

00:07:03.919 --> 00:07:07.389
&gt;&gt;Meier: --and sources of heat [laughs] than
you would want otherwise.

00:07:07.389 --> 00:07:11.800
You really want to be able to see this text
from a good five to ten feet away, assuming

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:14.259
you have a bigger kitchen than me.

00:07:14.259 --> 00:07:18.570
&gt;&gt;Chung: Have a look at the overflow menu.

00:07:18.570 --> 00:07:24.350
I wish they had an option where you can increase
the font size, but it, at least, I can't find

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.630
it from here.

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:30.380
What's interesting is that for each step,
you can go in and edit it.

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:32.340
Sometimes people like to deviate.

00:07:32.340 --> 00:07:33.340
&gt;&gt;Meier: That's nice.

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:34.340
Absolutely.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:35.850
There's not a recipe that I use that I haven't
modified slightly.

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:36.850
&gt;&gt;Chung: Exactly.

00:07:36.850 --> 00:07:39.180
&gt;&gt;Meier: You know what else would be really
nice here, I don't know if there's any support

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:42.210
for it, but to have the ability to add pictures
for each step.

00:07:42.210 --> 00:07:46.710
I find that's really useful if I know if it
looks the way it's supposed to, if I've done

00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:47.889
things the right way.

00:07:47.889 --> 00:07:50.460
Like when they say "brown it", how brown is
it supposed to be?

00:07:50.460 --> 00:07:52.500
Those sorts of things would be really nice.

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:55.340
A picture of the finished product and also
a picture of each step.

00:07:55.340 --> 00:07:57.490
&gt;&gt;Chung: Great suggestion.

00:07:57.490 --> 00:07:58.979
You can capture it for motivation.

00:07:58.979 --> 00:07:59.979
&gt;&gt;Meier: Absolutely.

00:07:59.979 --> 00:08:04.039
This is what I would do: I would do the recipe
and I would take a photo of each step so I

00:08:04.039 --> 00:08:06.259
was able to see the process of going through.

00:08:06.259 --> 00:08:10.069
And potentially, even the ability to add a
video.

00:08:10.069 --> 00:08:12.250
If I record the whole thing of how it all
went.

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:14.400
I see we've got Roman on screen.

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:15.940
What do you think, Roman?

00:08:15.940 --> 00:08:20.100
If you've had a chance to look at this app,
what are your thoughts from the UI perspective?

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:24.699
&gt;&gt;Roman Nurik: I haven't had a chance to take
a full look, but just from looking at what

00:08:24.699 --> 00:08:31.270
you guys are showing now, the same common
problems that we see everywhere are showing

00:08:31.270 --> 00:08:32.270
up in this app.

00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:36.840
And they're not really problems, it's just
I think probably the lack of a tablet-optimized

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:39.190
UI inside a tablet.

00:08:39.190 --> 00:08:43.580
One thing I wanted to mention was just on
the very home screen, I guess the top level

00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:51.930
screen, that has that massive dashboard, I
just wanted to make a shout out for, I guess,

00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:55.821
against dashboards and using dashboards, especially
on tablets.

00:08:55.821 --> 00:09:03.580
There are lots and lots of different ways
you can show a top level screen.

00:09:03.580 --> 00:09:08.620
Some of those ways are actually listed in
our design guidelines under the app structure

00:09:08.620 --> 00:09:09.620
pattern.

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:13.620
I definitely recommend taking a look there
to see how you can get away from a dashboard.

00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:18.570
You don't necessarily have to completely remove
the dashboard, but one thing you could do

00:09:18.570 --> 00:09:24.040
is potentially include content break there,
so when you're showing the big icons, the

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:27.820
big buttons, to get into the section, show
the preview of the content that you're about

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:29.600
to see when you tap into that section.

00:09:29.600 --> 00:09:31.790
It's just one of the things that--

00:09:31.790 --> 00:09:32.790
&gt;&gt;Chung: Some pictures, right.

00:09:32.790 --> 00:09:36.190
Some pictures of the dishes that you're trying
to prepare.

00:09:36.190 --> 00:09:37.850
That's great.

00:09:37.850 --> 00:09:40.690
Let's go back to recipes.

00:09:40.690 --> 00:09:44.740
As I was testing this application, I tried
to add a new dish.

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:48.900
At first, I thought, this "Add" button represented
it, but instead--

00:09:48.900 --> 00:09:51.930
&gt;&gt;Meier: That's a step within the existing
recipe.

00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:52.930
&gt;&gt;Chung: Right, right.

00:09:52.930 --> 00:09:56.520
But instead, what I was looking for is hidden
in the overflow menu.

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:57.530
&gt;&gt;Meier: Oh, I see.

00:09:57.530 --> 00:09:58.530
&gt;&gt;Chung: "New recipes."

00:09:58.530 --> 00:10:05.240
So I think it would be great to expose this
feature on the action bar if there's space.

00:10:05.240 --> 00:10:06.240
&gt;&gt;Meier: Yeah, definitely.

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:08.630
I think there is plenty of space in the action
bar for that.

00:10:08.630 --> 00:10:14.030
"Add recipes" seems like it would be one of
the main features of what you want to do within

00:10:14.030 --> 00:10:16.300
an app like this.

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:17.300
Absolutely.

00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:21.530
&gt;&gt;Chung: Let's have a quick look at "shopping
list."

00:10:21.530 --> 00:10:26.100
You can have various shopping lists associated
with the recipes that we looked at.

00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:28.270
Let's say you've decided on what to cook for
dinner.

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:33.570
Then you can quickly transfer the list of
items into your shopping list.

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:39.779
I think it's a good use case where at home,
the user might be using a tablet to come up

00:10:39.779 --> 00:10:45.570
with the list of recipes, and then, based
on the list of recipes, you come up with a

00:10:45.570 --> 00:10:46.570
shopping list.

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:50.920
Then if you support something like syncing
with the Cloud, when you take your Android

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:57.190
device out, you can have the shopping list
with you at the grocery store, where it can

00:10:57.190 --> 00:10:58.870
mark off various items.

00:10:58.870 --> 00:11:01.300
&gt;&gt;Meier: Do you know if this has the ability
to sync?

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:02.970
Like, are you signing in at any point?

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:07.640
If I have my tablet, which lives in my kitchen,
or at least in my living room and kitchen,

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:11.491
to be able to do recipes, can I sync that
up with my phone so I have my shopping list

00:11:11.491 --> 00:11:12.540
with me?

00:11:12.540 --> 00:11:16.839
&gt;&gt;Chung: I think there was, but I can't recall.

00:11:16.839 --> 00:11:20.630
But assuming it does, I think it would be
a good use case.

00:11:20.630 --> 00:11:21.630
&gt;&gt;Meier: Definitely.

00:11:21.630 --> 00:11:22.630
Nice.

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:23.630
That would be my wish list.

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:29.160
I think, for me, to just go ahead and start
using this would be pictures, lots of pictures.

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:33.420
Food, eating, and preparing food: a big part
of that is visual.

00:11:33.420 --> 00:11:37.990
Being able to see what the cauliflower cheese
soup looks like is going to make it much more

00:11:37.990 --> 00:11:40.850
likely for me to actually create it.

00:11:40.850 --> 00:11:44.670
Certainly, whenever I'm using cookbooks and
recipes, seeing that picture of what it's

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:46.970
going to end up like is a big thing for me.

00:11:46.970 --> 00:11:47.970
&gt;&gt;Chung: Definitely.

00:11:47.970 --> 00:11:52.529
I will also say that for this kind of app,
where initially, there's a bunch of data entry

00:11:52.529 --> 00:11:58.779
involved, you might want to think of ways
to make it easier for users, because I imagine

00:11:58.779 --> 00:12:03.960
if it becomes too cumbersome to enter a lot
of text, you will experience a lot of drop

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:04.960
offs.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:10.360
You may think of ways to maybe support upscanning
for barcodes and stuff like that that would

