These are the recipes that most people have
been raving about.

00:35:18.430 --> 00:35:20.150
If I open the app straight--.

00:35:20.150 --> 00:35:24.539
It was featured on Google Play, I hit install,
open, boom, and this is what I saw?

00:35:24.539 --> 00:35:28.510
Suddenly, I have much more incentive than
just from seeing this big logo.

00:35:28.510 --> 00:35:31.430
I can be like, "Oh, those Oreo bowls look
phenomenal."

00:35:31.430 --> 00:35:36.559
[laughs] Straight away, it's like, "I don't
need much for that.

00:35:36.559 --> 00:35:37.970
I've got cream cheese and Oreos.

00:35:37.970 --> 00:35:39.789
I'm pretty much already sold."

00:35:39.789 --> 00:35:43.280
Straight away, you're scrolling through things.

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:45.109
And again, getting really hungry.

00:35:45.109 --> 00:35:48.980
Which is, again, why we want to make sure
that you don't have this long load time of

00:35:48.980 --> 00:35:50.099
each recipe clicking in.

00:35:50.099 --> 00:35:53.780
I just want to be able to scroll through this
list and see anything which looks awesome,

00:35:53.780 --> 00:35:58.619
and be like, "Oh wow, I totally need to make
skewered honey balsamic vinegar kebabs."

00:35:58.619 --> 00:36:01.560
Wow, I need to stop.

00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:02.560
[laughs]

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:07.339
&gt;&gt;Nurik: A commenter on HBC 2000 also mentions
this app might be a little more attractive

00:36:07.339 --> 00:36:10.400
if they used the light hollow theme on the
action bar instead of the dark

00:36:10.400 --> 00:36:11.400
&gt;&gt;Meier: That's true.

00:36:11.400 --> 00:36:13.940
The consistency there is definitely an issue.

00:36:13.940 --> 00:36:17.880
&gt;&gt;Chung: They have the default blue line here.

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:19.299
&gt;&gt;Meier: [laughs] With the red straight underneath.

00:36:19.299 --> 00:36:23.240
&gt;&gt;Chung: The red line is part of their brand.

00:36:23.240 --> 00:36:25.430
You can definitely theme a little bit.

00:36:25.430 --> 00:36:26.430
&gt;&gt;Meier: Hmm.

00:36:26.430 --> 00:36:27.430
Exactly.

00:36:27.430 --> 00:36:31.420
Given that you do have this strong color branding,
you may want to consider using, changing the

00:36:31.420 --> 00:36:35.010
color of your action bar to match the recipe
color branding.

00:36:35.010 --> 00:36:36.519
That's definitely something you can do.

00:36:36.519 --> 00:36:41.660
But I'm intrigued by Roman's idea of switching
the whole theme around to something dark and

00:36:41.660 --> 00:36:43.640
then emphasizing the images more.

00:36:43.640 --> 00:36:44.640
&gt;&gt;Chung: Definitely.

00:36:44.640 --> 00:36:50.619
&gt;&gt;Meier: I'd also point out that the actual
text star that they're using there is a serif

00:36:50.619 --> 00:36:55.950
font, which works really well if you're reading
a book or something like that, but it doesn't

00:36:55.950 --> 00:36:59.520
work quite as well on computer screens, and
particularly when you're reading it from a

00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:00.520
distance.

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:05.079
You'll notice most presentations tend to use
a sans-serif font like an Arial or a Helvetica

00:37:05.079 --> 00:37:07.040
or something like that.

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:10.760
And again, you may be browsing it sitting
down on your couch, but you're going to be

00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:14.920
using it in a kitchen on a stand, again, from
a distance.

00:37:14.920 --> 00:37:17.609
So again, it's great that they let you bump
up the text size.

00:37:17.609 --> 00:37:21.730
I would probably prefer here, either an option
or just a default, to be a sans-serif.

00:37:21.730 --> 00:37:22.730
&gt;&gt;Chung: That's a good point.

00:37:22.730 --> 00:37:27.400
&gt;&gt;Nurik: One of the other things I wanted
to mention on fonts is-- And this is unfortunate.

00:37:27.400 --> 00:37:32.069
[gong sounds] We just, I guess if we just
didn't have time or if we didn't plan on it,

00:37:32.069 --> 00:37:37.500
but the new font of Android, the new typeface,
is Roboto, obviously.

00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:40.510
There's no serif version of Roboto, though.

00:37:40.510 --> 00:37:41.640
&gt;&gt;Meier: That's interesting.

00:37:41.640 --> 00:37:47.589
&gt;&gt;Nurik: Basically, a lot of the improvements,
a lot of the core image and design philosophy

00:37:47.589 --> 00:37:49.760
of Android is around the typography.

00:37:49.760 --> 00:37:54.049
So you're missing a lot of that by using Android
serif.

00:37:54.049 --> 00:37:58.470
Having said that, there's also Roboto Thin
and Roboto Light.

00:37:58.470 --> 00:38:03.740
When you have text that's larger, let's say
in the 30 or the 40 sps, Roboto Light can

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:08.020
really give it a sense of class or elegance.

00:38:08.020 --> 00:38:12.020
Coupled with increasing the font size, you
may want to consider using the different weights

00:38:12.020 --> 00:38:13.220
of Roboto.

00:38:13.220 --> 00:38:14.220
There are several.

00:38:14.220 --> 00:38:21.510
Actually, as of Jelly Bean, we bundle very,
very many weights of Roboto, so you have more

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:22.510
options.

00:38:22.510 --> 00:38:23.570
Or you can just bundle the TTF directly here
if you can.

00:38:23.570 --> 00:38:25.190
&gt;&gt;Meier: Outstanding.

00:38:25.190 --> 00:38:26.190
Cool.

00:38:26.190 --> 00:38:30.730
That was our gong in the background, so we're
ready to move on to our next app, which is

00:38:30.730 --> 00:38:32.059
one of mine.

00:38:32.059 --> 00:38:34.579
TripIt's hard to demo without having some
trips in there.

00:38:34.579 --> 00:38:39.290
We've only got a few minutes, so let's have
a look at IMDb instead.

00:38:39.290 --> 00:38:42.450
Based on the two apps that I've looked at
today, you can get a fair idea of how I enjoy

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:44.280
to spend some of my spare time.

00:38:44.280 --> 00:38:47.170
But I'm a big fan of the IMDb app.

00:38:47.170 --> 00:38:49.809
This is a great example of an app which users--.

00:38:49.809 --> 00:38:52.190
It's very much its own custom branding.

00:38:52.190 --> 00:38:53.540
This doesn't look like hollow.

00:38:53.540 --> 00:38:55.170
It doesn't not look like it either.

00:38:55.170 --> 00:38:57.369
But it definitely looks like IMDb.

00:38:57.369 --> 00:39:04.870
We have this consistent gray gradient branding
with the quite distinctive IMDb gold logo.

00:39:04.870 --> 00:39:09.480
And again, if we look at what we've been talking
about so far with today's apps, we load this

00:39:09.480 --> 00:39:11.980
up and straight away, I'm presented with a
wall of images.

00:39:11.980 --> 00:39:15.349
I've got video front and center and a scrolling
marquee.

00:39:15.349 --> 00:39:20.470
I've got another scrolling marquee down here
of awesome-looking movie posters.

00:39:20.470 --> 00:39:24.099
Coming soon is the same.

00:39:24.099 --> 00:39:27.630
This is basically full of imagery.

00:39:27.630 --> 00:39:30.990
That, I think, it makes for a really compelling
experience, because straight away, you've

00:39:30.990 --> 00:39:35.560
got things to look at, you've got things to
scroll, you've got things to browse.

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:38.200
Overall, I quite like that.

00:39:38.200 --> 00:39:41.990
It's not a standard action bar, because it's
too high to be a standard action bar.

00:39:41.990 --> 00:39:46.930
They've done some interesting things here,
like this overflow menu is clearly not a default

00:39:46.930 --> 00:39:51.619
of the standard overflow menu, or even a standard
pop up menu, which a lot of people use to

00:39:51.619 --> 00:39:53.410
simulate that effect.

00:39:53.410 --> 00:39:56.010
I don't know.

00:39:56.010 --> 00:40:00.569
To me, it almost works in that it's got the
branding, it's got the gray and the gold,

00:40:00.569 --> 00:40:05.260
which is obviously the theme they're going
throughout, but the weird rounded corners

00:40:05.260 --> 00:40:10.000
and the drop shadow strikes me as being a
little off.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:13.270
This is the first time where I click something
on the app, and suddenly, it doesn't quite

00:40:13.270 --> 00:40:15.049
feel like a native app anymore.

00:40:15.049 --> 00:40:16.180
What do you think, Roman?

00:40:16.180 --> 00:40:24.319
&gt;&gt;Nurik: Yeah, I do want to call out, like
you said, the drop shadows, also some of the

00:40:24.319 --> 00:40:29.789
gradients, like the title bar or rather the
fake action bar has this stark gradient.

00:40:29.789 --> 00:40:34.670
One of the things we generally recommend,
This is not like a "You must not use gradients

00:40:34.670 --> 00:40:39.740
on Android" or anything, but we definitely
recommend using fewer visual effects.

00:40:39.740 --> 00:40:47.470
Things like drop shadows, things like gradients,
things like glosses.

00:40:47.470 --> 00:40:52.339
They clash with the minimalistic, cleaner
style of hollow.

00:40:52.339 --> 00:41:00.299
When a user gets their Galaxy Nexus or one
of their ICS devices, they're presented with

00:41:00.299 --> 00:41:02.619
somewhat minimal UI apps.

00:41:02.619 --> 00:41:07.950
Apps that give you content and minimize the
number of pixels that are dedicated purely

00:41:07.950 --> 00:41:13.230
to aesthetics of the Chrome, of the surrounding
elements of the app.

00:41:13.230 --> 00:41:20.470
Definitely minimizing that and using some
of the simpler, minimal styles would make

00:41:20.470 --> 00:41:21.470
more sense, I think.

00:41:21.470 --> 00:41:25.289
Then definitely using the stock action bar
and tweaking the styles.

00:41:25.289 --> 00:41:26.289
Like you can make that--.

00:41:26.289 --> 00:41:29.940
If you absolutely needed that bar to be taller,
you could tweak that using styles.

00:41:29.940 --> 00:41:31.180
You don't have to reimplement the action bar.

00:41:31.180 --> 00:41:34.380
&gt;&gt;Meier: In fact, I'd suggest that they probably
don't need to make it taller.

00:41:34.380 --> 00:41:37.680
It just feels stretched for no really good
reason.

00:41:37.680 --> 00:41:40.820
I like that they've used the standard search
widget here.

00:41:40.820 --> 00:41:42.030
That's great.

00:41:42.030 --> 00:41:48.019
These keys here, "movies", "TV", "celebs",
that, again, strikes me as a little odd, because

00:41:48.019 --> 00:41:51.490
they're not really action so much as navigation
cues.

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:55.790
As per the Android stands, I'd expect them
to be over on the left-hand side over here,

00:41:55.790 --> 00:41:57.450
next to the IMDb logo.

00:41:57.450 --> 00:42:01.320
Similarly, I expect this to behave like a
standard action bar.

00:42:01.320 --> 00:42:07.609
I'm looking for an up caret on the left here
so that I can return to this, to the main

00:42:07.609 --> 00:42:08.609
page.

00:42:08.609 --> 00:42:12.440
The navigation actually works the way it should,
but I'm missing some of those standard queues

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:14.519
that I'm really used to seeing.

00:42:14.519 --> 00:42:21.220
I'd like to see these as default, regular
tabs or something similar to that, rather

00:42:21.220 --> 00:42:23.769
than being actions when they're not really
actions.

00:42:23.769 --> 00:42:26.680
&gt;&gt;Chung: The general pattern goes on the action
bar on the left hand side.

00:42:26.680 --> 00:42:30.950
You have the icon followed by a navigation
control.

00:42:30.950 --> 00:42:35.289
Put everything else, like the action menu
items, on the right-hand side.

00:42:35.289 --> 00:42:36.309
&gt;&gt;Meier: Exactly.

00:42:36.309 --> 00:42:40.160
Things like "search," they've got in exactly
the right place.

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:43.619
Having all this stuff in the overflow menu,
again, makes sense.

00:42:43.619 --> 00:42:46.559
I want to highlight, as well, here, that they
have the ability to sign in.

00:42:46.559 --> 00:42:49.250
You can have an IMDb account and sign in.

00:42:49.250 --> 00:42:53.109
Presumably, things like your watch list, some
ratings history, and the ratings you provide

00:42:53.109 --> 00:42:55.450
are all then going to be part of it.

00:42:55.450 --> 00:43:00.119
What a lot of apps do wrong is that they don't
let you use anything until you've signed in.

00:43:00.119 --> 00:43:05.299
When you install it off Google Play, hit open,
the first thing you're presented with is this

00:43:05.299 --> 00:43:07.240
sign in screen.

00:43:07.240 --> 00:43:11.100
That's a real off-putter, because it's like,
"Well, I've not even looked at this app yet.

00:43:11.100 --> 00:43:16.259
I have no idea what it wants, and it wants
credentials, it wants me to create an account.

00:43:16.259 --> 00:43:18.390
I want to know what I'm getting into first."

00:43:18.390 --> 00:43:21.869
So I love that about this app, in that it
lets you experience the full app.

00:43:21.869 --> 00:43:27.109
It's not until you want to do something which
requires you to sign in that it actually asks

00:43:27.109 --> 00:43:28.109
you to do so.

00:43:28.109 --> 00:43:30.670
It also lets you do so as well here in the
overflow menu.

00:43:30.670 --> 00:43:35.600
That style of presenting as much as you can,
and then having additional features as an

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:38.859
incentive to actually sign in, I think it's
a really good pattern.

00:43:38.859 --> 00:43:40.809
&gt;&gt;Chung: Great point.

00:43:40.809 --> 00:43:43.559
&gt;&gt;Meier: Let's have a look.

00:43:43.559 --> 00:43:46.470
Otherwise, it works pretty much as you'd expect
it to.

00:43:46.470 --> 00:43:52.170
Let's have a look at Total Recall, a movie
remake which fills me with dread.

00:43:52.170 --> 00:43:54.300
I'm a huge fan of Philip K. Dick.

00:43:54.300 --> 00:43:57.460
The movie implementations are usually pretty
questionable.

00:43:57.460 --> 00:44:01.470
Total Recall, again, is a movie I really enjoyed
when I was younger, but--

00:44:01.470 --> 00:44:04.660
&gt;&gt;Off-camera engineer: [Terminator voice]
It's not a tumor!

00:44:04.660 --> 00:44:08.039
&gt;&gt;Meier: [laughs] That may be the wrong Schwarzenegger
movie, but nonetheless.

00:44:08.039 --> 00:44:14.369
I always wondered about Schwarzenegger in
the lead role of that.

00:44:14.369 --> 00:44:19.640
Colin Farrell is a better match, but I don't
know.

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:22.200
I'm apprehensive, to say the very least, about
this remake.

00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:26.920
In any case, you can see here, as soon as
we navigate in, again, we have a wall of pictures.

00:44:26.920 --> 00:44:30.279
We have a big image of the movie poster.

00:44:30.279 --> 00:44:31.410
We see the top bill cast.

00:44:31.410 --> 00:44:32.720
They're all here on the left.

00:44:32.720 --> 00:44:33.720
We have galleries.

00:44:33.720 --> 00:44:39.640
These aren't scrollable, so I guess you have
to hit "all" to see more of the images.

00:44:39.640 --> 00:44:41.799
This is interesting.

00:44:41.799 --> 00:44:43.339
They've got this pop up dialog.

00:44:43.339 --> 00:44:47.740
I hate, hate, hate pop up dialogs, particularly
when there's no obvious way to dismiss it.

00:44:47.740 --> 00:44:51.420
I'm going to guess that the back button does
the job.

00:44:51.420 --> 00:44:52.420
But I don't know.

00:44:52.420 --> 00:44:53.460
I feel like this could be done a little bit
neater.

00:44:53.460 --> 00:44:54.460
I like that--

00:44:54.460 --> 00:44:55.460
&gt;&gt;Chung: You could do it in place.

00:44:55.460 --> 00:44:56.470
&gt;&gt;Meier: --to be scrollable here.

00:44:56.470 --> 00:44:57.470
Just let me scroll through.

00:44:57.470 --> 00:45:01.970
&gt;&gt;Chung: Yeah, I saw your first inclination
on this section of the screen was to scroll.

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:06.200
&gt;&gt;Meier: Yeah, exactly, because they used
marquees elsewhere in the app, so I'd like

00:45:06.200 --> 00:45:10.579
to be able to just flick through here and
see all the cast without having to change

00:45:10.579 --> 00:45:11.579
contexts.

00:45:11.579 --> 00:45:12.579
Same with the gallery.

00:45:12.579 --> 00:45:16.369
If I click on an image, it actually goes to
the artist's page.

00:45:16.369 --> 00:45:17.640
That all makes sense.

00:45:17.640 --> 00:45:20.960
&gt;&gt;Chung: Let's check out how sharing is done
in this app.

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:22.859
&gt;&gt;Meier: Done the right way.

00:45:22.859 --> 00:45:23.999
&gt;&gt;Chung: As expected.

00:45:23.999 --> 00:45:24.999
That's great.

00:45:24.999 --> 00:45:26.220
&gt;&gt;Meier: Right icons, that's all nice.

00:45:26.220 --> 00:45:32.920
As you can see, they've really taken this
custom styling to the final degree.

00:45:32.920 --> 00:45:33.920
Everything is custom.

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:37.130
These dialogs don't look like normal Android
dialogs.

00:45:37.130 --> 00:45:38.130
They're quite tall.

00:45:38.130 --> 00:45:41.269
They've got the action, not the action bar,
but the title bar on top.

00:45:41.269 --> 00:45:45.240
Now, there's nothing wrong with customizing
the look and feel of these sorts of things,

00:45:45.240 --> 00:45:50.390
but particularly dialogs, which, our general
guidance is to use dialogs only when you're

00:45:50.390 --> 00:45:53.059
doing a system level thing.

00:45:53.059 --> 00:45:54.250
That's when you pop up the dialog.

00:45:54.250 --> 00:45:58.599
It's like when WiFi is being disabled or if
you want user authentication.

00:45:58.599 --> 00:46:02.609
Something which is more than just the app,
beyond the context of the app, that's really

00:46:02.609 --> 00:46:04.150
the only time you should be using dialogs.

00:46:04.150 --> 00:46:08.289
If you're doing that, then they should look
like the system dialogs so that people know

00:46:08.289 --> 00:46:10.089
what to expect.

00:46:10.089 --> 00:46:14.569
Here, What I would say is that rather than
saying you should be using standard dialogs,

00:46:14.569 --> 00:46:18.809
which would, in fairness, look really weird
on top of their custom UI, is see if you can

00:46:18.809 --> 00:46:21.089
get out of using dialogs at all.

00:46:21.089 --> 00:46:25.320
Whether doing things in place or having a
different fragment switch out, some other

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:29.599
way of navigating which doesn't pop something
on top of what you're doing.

00:46:29.599 --> 00:46:32.290
Do you hate dialogs as much as I do?

00:46:32.290 --> 00:46:33.290
&gt;&gt;Chung: Not quite.

00:46:33.290 --> 00:46:34.460
&gt;&gt;Meier: Not as much?

00:46:34.460 --> 00:46:40.380
&gt;&gt;Chung: I agree with your assessment in this
particular scenario where if this implementation

00:46:40.380 --> 00:46:43.559
wasn't in place, transition would be better.

00:46:43.559 --> 00:46:47.930
It felt like I was focusing on the right-hand
side of the screen.

00:46:47.930 --> 00:46:51.190
If the dialog pops, it just breaks the continuity.

00:46:51.190 --> 00:46:53.670
&gt;&gt;Meier: What about you, Roman?

00:46:53.670 --> 00:46:56.250
In the couple of minutes we've got remaining?

00:46:56.250 --> 00:46:57.769
&gt;&gt;Nurik: I generally agree.

00:46:57.769 --> 00:46:59.510
I generally hate dialogs.

00:46:59.510 --> 00:47:02.450
I, more than anything, hate progress and loading
dialogs.

00:47:02.450 --> 00:47:05.039
&gt;&gt;Meier: Oh, yeah, well, they are the devil,
clearly.

00:47:05.039 --> 00:47:10.540
&gt;&gt;Nurik: [laughs] In this case, I think the
dialog is really just a shortcut.

00:47:10.540 --> 00:47:17.170
I feel like in a lot of cases when a developer
doesn't really have a great idea of what's

00:47:17.170 --> 00:47:20.920
the best possible way to present something,
a dialog is a shortcut.

00:47:20.920 --> 00:47:22.530
I've definitely done it myself.

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:25.539
I've definitely just said, "Oh, just make
it a dialog."

00:47:25.539 --> 00:47:32.339
But definitely, a more complete, a better
solution would be just another fragment gliding

00:47:32.339 --> 00:47:34.789
in, or something of that nature.

00:47:34.789 --> 00:47:38.099
It's tough to avoid dialogs always because
they're very tempting.

00:47:38.099 --> 00:47:39.839
But do try to avoid them.

00:47:39.839 --> 00:47:40.839
&gt;&gt;Meier: Yeah.

00:47:40.839 --> 00:47:41.839
That's a really good point.

00:47:41.839 --> 00:47:43.559
Dialogs do represent, often, a shortcut.

00:47:43.559 --> 00:47:47.700
It's a way of being able to, as a developer,
when you haven't really thought through all

00:47:47.700 --> 00:47:49.809
of the work flows, it's like, "I need to present
this information.

00:47:49.809 --> 00:47:51.260
How can I do that?"

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:52.510
A dialog is the easiest.

00:47:52.510 --> 00:47:54.410
It's like doing a print line as a debugging--

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:55.819
&gt;&gt;Chung: It's like a catch all.

00:47:55.819 --> 00:47:56.819
&gt;&gt;Meier: Exactly.

00:47:56.819 --> 00:47:59.559
It's like using a toast to know whether or
not something's happened.

00:47:59.559 --> 00:48:01.770
We all do that as part of our development
process.

